dismissalText.commentary: Stephen Fleming c Tendulkar b Srinath 30 (59b 4x4 0x6 85m) SR: 50.84

dismissalComment.html: a big blow for New Zealand, their key man goes, and to a rather poor shot too, trying to smack a short lifting ball across the line, had no width to work with just outside off stump, miscues it straight up to Tendulkar at mid off,        he pouches the simplest of catches as it lobs straight up to him, and New Zealand sit on the rather  embarrassing score of 60/5 in near ideal batting conditions, a nothing shot from Fleming, he was just looking to take charge again after being forced to settle down after the splurge of wickets at the other end, but picked the wrong ball with which to start the charge

commentTextItems.html: and another one from Kaif, replaying the same  stroke, heaving the ball again to the midwicket fence and getting   India home extremely comfortably in the end

commentPostTextItems.html: So that ends New Zealand's defence of their total, India getting  home comfortably in the end, seven wickets and almost 10 overs in hand

India notch up their seventh win in a row, maintaining their run of  good form leading into the semifinals of this World Cup.  New Zealand on the other hand will be disappointed with their  performance in this crunch game, and they must hope for Sri Lanka  to lose to Zimbabwe tomorrow to get through to the semifinals.

India were boosted hugely by their suddenly-potent pace  triumvirate, Zaheer Khan doing the bulk of the damage today with  four wickets.  And after Shane Bond had India reeling at 21 for three, Mohammad  Kaif and Rahul Dravid played sensible, solid cricket to take their   side home.
Man of the Match: Zaheer Khan
Join CricInfo tomorrow for the live coverage of the final two Super   Six matches. Sri Lanka take on Zimbabwe in a crucial game at East  London in a day match, starting at 0800 GMT
Australia and Kenya clash at Durban in a day-nighter, starting at 1230 GMT. Till tomorrow, goodbye.

stories.title: India's seventh win in a row achieved with ease over NZ
stories.summary: India had batsmen in Mohammad Kaif and Rahul Dravid who produced the goods when they mattered, something New Zealand couldn't generate in their own innings, and they inflicted a seven-wicket loss that should spell the end of New Zealand's World Cup
